---
<SiteLayout site="migratingmammals" title="Guide to Managing Health Records Abroad" description="Learn how to organize your medical history, transfer prescriptions, and manage your health records when moving abroad." canonical="https://migratingmammals.com/guide-health-records-abroad" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Health Records Abroad</h1>
      <p>Digital records, prescription transfers, and continuity of care.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section">
      <p>Ensuring a smooth transition of your healthcare is vital when relocating. This guide explains how to gather your medical history, prepare your prescriptions, and set up your healthcare in a new country.</p>

      <h2>Gathering Your Medical History</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <p>Before you leave, you must obtain your medical records. Do not assume your new doctor can easily request them across international borders.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Request Copies:</strong> Ask your primary care physician and any specialists for a complete copy of your records. Digital formats (PDFs on a secure USB drive) are usually best.</li>
          <li><strong>Vaccination Records:</strong> Ensure your immunization records are up to date and physically documented, especially if you have children.</li>
          <li><strong>Translation:</strong> If moving to a non-English speaking country, consider getting vital summaries (like surgical history or chronic condition notes) translated by a certified medical translator.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <h2>Managing Prescriptions</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <p>Your current prescriptions will likely not be valid in your destination country.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Stockpile (Legally):</strong> Ask your doctor for a 3- to 6-month supply of your essential medications to tide you over while you establish care abroad. Check your airline and destination country's rules on traveling with medication.</li>
          <li><strong>Generic Names:</strong> Medication brand names vary wildly around the world. Write down the active ingredients (generic names) and dosages of everything you take.</li>
          <li><strong>Find a Local Doctor:</strong> Once you arrive, prioritize making an appointment with a local general practitioner. Bring your records and generic medication list to get local prescriptions issued.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <h2>Digital Health Passports</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <p>Many countries are moving toward centralized digital health systems. Be prepared to register for your destination's national health app or digital portal once you receive your local health number or residency card.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>Cross-Links and Related Information</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <p>Gathering your health records is a crucial task for Phase 3 of your <a href="/moving-abroad-checklist">Moving Abroad Checklist</a>.</p>
        <p>If you are bringing an emotional support animal or a pet with specific medical needs, refer to our <a href="/guide-pet-relocation">Pet Relocation Guide</a>. You may also need to show vaccination records when applying for your initial <a href="/guide-tax-residency-abroad">visas and residency</a>.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <h3>How do I take my medical records abroad?</h3>
        <p>Request a complete physical or digital copy of your records from your current doctor. Ensure you have the generic names of all medications, as brand names vary by country.</p>

        <h3>Can I fill a foreign prescription abroad?</h3>
        <p>Usually, no. Pharmacies typically require a prescription from a local doctor. You will need to take your medical records to a new doctor in your destination country to get a local prescription.</p>

        <h3>Do I need to translate my medical records?</h3>
        <p>If you are moving to a country where English is not the primary language of healthcare, having your key records translated by a certified medical translator is highly recommended.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
